Content: Some query.

@OpenAI ChatGpt -- the AI taking the world by storm -- uses the corpus of the Internet, it performs a thousand "micro-plagiarisms" to answer any query.   It doesn't 'know' anything. There is zero 'intelligence' inside of it. There is zero reasoning ability.   It is a remix bot.  It remixes the vast extant record of HUMAN intelligence to provide any answer. 

Now: it is damned impressive at what it does. And VERY useful.  In my opinion, it passes the Turing Test -- even if it DOES use a 'parlour trick' under the hood to do it. 
However it does it, it DOES do it. 

And it is a 'moment' -- just like Mosaic, the iPhone and Bitcoin were massive moments. 

But there's a whole lotta 'electronic superstition' swirling around what this is -- thought I'd dispel the mysticism

ChatGPT is a powerful AI chatbot that can answer any question you ask it. It does this by using the corpus of the internet to perform a thousand "micro-plagiarisms" to find the best answer to your question.

ChatGPT doesn't "know" anything. There is zero "intelligence" inside of it. There is zero reasoning ability. It is a remix bot. It remixes the vast extant record of HUMAN intelligence to provide any answer.

Now: it is damned impressive at what it does. And VERY useful. In my opinion, it passes the Turing Test -- even if it DOES use a 'parlour trick' under the hood to do it.

However it does it, it DOES do it. And it is a 'moment' -- just like Mosaic, the iPhone and Bitcoin were massive moments.

But there's a whole lotta 'electronic superstition' swirling around what this is -- thought I'd dispel the mysticism.

ChatGPT is a powerful tool, but it's important to remember that it's not a replacement for human intelligence. It's a tool that can help us to access and process information more effectively, but it can't think for itself.

We should use ChatGPT with caution and be aware of its limitations. But it's definitely a tool that has the potential to change the way we live and work.

Content: The query string is the part of the URL that starts with a question mark (?) and contains key-value pairs separated by an ampersand (&). For example, in the URL /search?q=node.js&page=1, the query parameters are q and page.

When a request is made to this URL, the id parameter value can be accessed using https://t.co/97YC2tVFPp.On the other hand, req.query is used to access query parameters, which are part of the URL query string.

* How many of the queries are exactly the same (caching helps avoid cost)

The main drivers of BigQuery cost for Data Studio are:
* The rows in the table being queried (for GA4 this is events per day)
* The bytes in the columns in the query (varies depending on query, we use an average)
Don't forget about voice search. Optimize your content for voice search queries.

In the NGDB framework, we create a taxonomy and survey 40+ neural graph reasoning models that can potentially serve as Neural Query Engines under 3 main categories: Graphs (theory and expressiveness), Modeling (graph learning), and Queries (what can we answer).

7/n https://t.co/EDuJDUiaEZ

What‚Äôs the difference between NGDBs and vector DBs? 

Vector DBs are fast and encoder-independent consuming embeddings from all kinds of models. Though they are limited to a few distance functions and lack query answering capabilities, they fit well into the NGDB blueprint!

6/n https://t.co/xIk8ZiRDRb

Thanks to GNNs, NGDBs can answer either the entire query graph at once or execute them sequentially. We don‚Äôt need any explicit indexes - the latent space formed by a neural encoder *is* the single uniform index.

5/n https://t.co/2zoHT944nb

Broadly, NGDBs are equipped to answer both ‚Äúwhat is there?‚Äù and ‚Äúwhat is missing?‚Äù queries whereas standard graph DBs are limited to traversal-only scenarios assuming the graph is complete.

4/n https://t.co/FrXRAsVm7u

What are NGDBs? While their architecture might look similar to traditional DBs with Storage and Query Engine, the essential difference is in ditching symbolic edge traversal and answering queries in the latent space (including logical operators).

3/n https://t.co/uB622mgUBx

üëâ Generation: Finally, the encoded query and passage representations are combined and fed into a generation model, such as a transformer-based language model like GPT-3, to generate the final output

3/

üëâ Retrieval: The encoded query is then used to retrieve a set of relevant passages from the indexed corpus using the retrieval algorithm

2/

üëâ Query encoding: When a user enters a query, the query is encoded using a query encoder, which is typically a neural network, such as BERT, that encodes the text into a fixed-length vector (list format for mathematical analysis) representation

1/
üëâ Indexing: First, a large corpus of text data is indexed using a retrieval algorithm such as dense passage retrieval (DPR). This involves encoding the text passages and building an index to efficiently retrieve relevant passages in response to a given query
